19
00:02:19.853 --> 00:02:23.043
Incoming livestream: Where does confidential computing come with agentic AI?

20
00:02:23.863 --> 00:02:24.613
Incoming livestream: Okay.

21
00:02:25.273 --> 00:02:30.152
Incoming livestream: If there are questions that can't wait till the end, please ask me through the session.

22
00:02:30.372 --> 00:02:35.703
Incoming livestream: Okay, so this is the industry definition for confidential AI.

23
00:02:35.983 --> 00:02:44.862
Incoming livestream: It is the overlay of AI on confidential computing, or if you think about it the other way, using confidential computing for protecting AI.

24
00:02:45.213 --> 00:03:02.053
Incoming livestream: So what's confidential computing? Very quickly, it has three pieces to it. Number one, you provide data in use protection by running your applications, your workloads, in hardware-protected environments called trusted execution environments.

25
00:03:02.913 --> 00:03:03.633
Incoming livestream: Okay?

26
00:03:03.803 --> 00:03:05.923
Incoming livestream: Everything that runs in there.

27
00:03:06.503 --> 00:03:13.942
Incoming livestream: Is encrypted, and it's in the control of the owner of that application workload data, whichever it is.

28
00:03:14.143 --> 00:03:18.923
Incoming livestream: Okay? And the third important property of confidential computing is

29
00:03:19.423 --> 00:03:27.072
Incoming livestream: You're gonna get what is called an attestation, which says, this is exactly what the environment in which you are running it.

30
00:03:27.363 --> 00:03:30.973
Incoming livestream: It's gonna tell you The hardware it is in.

31
00:03:31.473 --> 00:03:35.723
Incoming livestream: What's the firmware that's running there? What's the software that's running there?

32
00:03:35.863 --> 00:03:42.533
Incoming livestream: And if you are happy with it, that's when you interact with it, give it secrets, give it keys, all kinds of things.

33
00:03:43.073 --> 00:03:46.783
Incoming livestream: And why are we so interested in confidential computing?

34
00:03:47.333 --> 00:03:53.252
Incoming livestream: You can see on the right side of the picture there, it gives you some good protections.

35
00:03:53.373 --> 00:04:01.203
Incoming livestream: Okay? It gives you protections from day zeros to some degree, It protects you from the…

36
00:04:01.563 --> 00:04:06.133
Incoming livestream: Administrators of your infrastructure, whether it's on-prem or in the cloud.

37
00:04:07.183 --> 00:04:12.523
Incoming livestream: It gives you protection from other tenants that are running on the same infrastructure.

38
00:04:14.203 --> 00:04:18.022
Incoming livestream: Okay? So confidential computing that way gives you

39
00:04:18.063 --> 00:04:36.063
Incoming livestream: the protection from the infrastructure on which your workloads are running. You don't need to worry about, hey, this cloud operator could get access to what I'm doing, this cloud operator could have a rogue administrator that takes a snapshot of your virtual machine or your container, and they got all your secrets.

40
00:04:36.063 --> 00:04:41.382
Incoming livestream: All of those threat vectors, Disappear for the most part with confidential computing.

41
00:04:41.853 --> 00:04:45.823
Incoming livestream: And for AI workloads, that's why it's very important.

42
00:04:45.933 --> 00:04:54.263
Incoming livestream: Okay, it protects your models, it protects your data. If you're doing Gen AI stuff, it protects your prompts, your context windows, all of that stuff.

43
00:04:54.673 --> 00:04:56.603
Incoming livestream: Ken, I'm gonna show you how, okay?

44
00:04:58.373 --> 00:05:01.982
Incoming livestream: there are two models for confidential AI, okay? One is…

45
00:05:03.093 --> 00:05:11.053
Incoming livestream: running everything in confidential computing on CPUs, okay? I'm an Intel guy, so I have to talk about this use case, okay?

46
00:05:11.683 --> 00:05:15.642
Incoming livestream: It's good for inferencing, it's good for certain model sizes.

47
00:05:15.873 --> 00:05:18.833
Incoming livestream: Okay, 10 billion model, 10 billion parameters.

48
00:05:19.383 --> 00:05:24.812
Incoming livestream: CPUs with, you know, matrix extensions in the infrastructure.

49
00:05:25.203 --> 00:05:26.323
Incoming livestream: do pretty good.

50
00:05:26.783 --> 00:05:28.492
Incoming livestream: Okay? But…

51
00:05:28.823 --> 00:05:37.943
Incoming livestream: that's not enough. We know that. So that's why there is this second model, which is called the hybrid model, or the accelerated computing model, where

52
00:05:38.073 --> 00:05:41.382
Incoming livestream: you work in a combination of CPUs and GPUs.

53
00:05:42.043 --> 00:05:45.293
Incoming livestream: Okay? Intel CPUs have confidential computing.

54
00:05:45.753 --> 00:05:48.543
Incoming livestream: NVIDIA GPUs have confidential computing.

55
00:05:49.033 --> 00:05:51.283
Incoming livestream: So you can get them together.

56
00:05:51.513 --> 00:06:05.332
Incoming livestream: And you can have a good end-to-end story of confidential computing going from CPUs into GPUs. So, essentially, it is one extended trusted execution environment between CPUs and GPUs.

57
00:06:06.013 --> 00:06:09.453
Incoming livestream: Okay? There are two models for doing it.

58
00:06:09.783 --> 00:06:14.083
Incoming livestream: In the near term, you know, it's called a software-based model.

59
00:06:14.263 --> 00:06:18.983
Incoming livestream: You know, for folks who are familiar, they call it the bounce buffer solution, where

60
00:06:19.173 --> 00:06:23.113
Incoming livestream: the CPU writes into a buffer, it's an encrypted form.

61
00:06:23.393 --> 00:06:28.703
Incoming livestream: The GPU picks it up from the buffer, and the CPU and the GPU share the secret.

62
00:06:28.843 --> 00:06:37.983
Incoming livestream: So, things are encrypted, put on the buffer, GPUs pick up from there. In the encrypted form, they have the secret, so they decrypt it, and they run it in the GPUs.

63
00:06:38.253 --> 00:06:41.803
Incoming livestream: But in the longer term, year and a half, two years out.

64
00:06:42.413 --> 00:06:45.783
Incoming livestream: You don't need this software solution, it's all done in hardware.

65
00:06:46.213 --> 00:06:48.783
Incoming livestream: The PCIe bus gets encrypted.

66
00:06:48.983 --> 00:07:03.773
Incoming livestream: And then there is a negotiation between the CPUs and the GPUs on how they trust each other, and the proofs for trust, and then they pass that information in a very, very efficient way between the CPUs and the GPUs.

67
00:07:04.163 --> 00:07:06.072
Incoming livestream: By the way, you guys can hear me okay, right?

68
00:07:06.353 --> 00:07:07.242
Incoming livestream: Okay, thank you.

69
00:07:07.953 --> 00:07:09.973
Incoming livestream: Alright, that's a good answer, man.

70
00:07:11.593 --> 00:07:16.043
Incoming livestream: Alright, why do we care about confidential AI so much?

71
00:07:17.823 --> 00:07:34.083
Incoming livestream: it meets regulations very well, okay? Whether you look at DORA, whether you look at the new executive order from the US, or you look at the European Union AI Act, there are clear nuggets in all of them which point towards the use of confidential computing.

72
00:07:35.723 --> 00:07:36.963
Incoming livestream: That's why

73
00:07:37.093 --> 00:07:48.262
Incoming livestream: A lot of enterprises, a lot of cloud providers, everybody seemed to want to use confidential computing because it's a big checkmark item from a regulation side.

74
00:07:51.593 --> 00:07:59.792
Incoming livestream: You know, Intel has been doing confidential computing for a very long time, okay? I'm sure many of you are familiar with Intel SGX.

75
00:07:59.953 --> 00:08:03.302
Incoming livestream: Which was our first foray into confidential computing.

76
00:08:03.653 --> 00:08:06.983
Incoming livestream: It was not for the faint-hearted, Okay.

77
00:08:07.643 --> 00:08:12.472
Incoming livestream: It required quite a lot of hand-holding to make sure that

78
00:08:12.703 --> 00:08:17.022
Incoming livestream: You really know what you want to run inside confidential computing.

79
00:08:17.183 --> 00:08:20.523
Incoming livestream: But the positive side of that was.

80
00:08:20.793 --> 00:08:24.603
Incoming livestream: It was a very well-controlled security environment.

81
00:08:25.123 --> 00:08:28.402
Incoming livestream: with no access for anybody other than the CPU.

82
00:08:29.233 --> 00:08:34.133
Incoming livestream: Okay? But obviously, you know, everybody wants this concept called lift and shift.

83
00:08:34.533 --> 00:08:39.793
Incoming livestream: Where they can, take their containers, they can take their workloads.

84
00:08:39.963 --> 00:08:44.943
Incoming livestream: Run it in a regular environment, and then move it into a confidential computing environment.

85
00:08:45.083 --> 00:08:47.023
Incoming livestream: With the easy button, pretty much.

86
00:08:47.673 --> 00:08:52.732
Incoming livestream: That's where Intel TDX comes in, Trusted Domain Extensions, which is the second one.

87
00:08:53.043 --> 00:09:09.803
Incoming livestream: which guarantees you that you can take your virtual machines as they are today, the VM images, or your containers, and then run them in an environment which is confidential computing. And the way it manifests is following. You go to your cloud provider, Azure, GCP,

88
00:09:10.033 --> 00:09:13.672
Incoming livestream: IBM, Oracle in preview today.

89
00:09:14.673 --> 00:09:23.972
Incoming livestream: you say, hey, you get a VM instance, you know, whatever instance you have, 26 vCPUs with 128 gigabit RAM, right?

90
00:09:24.263 --> 00:09:30.062
Incoming livestream: you can go pick another instance which says confidential compute instance. Same properties.

91
00:09:30.623 --> 00:09:38.852
Incoming livestream: 68 GPU, CPUs, 128 gigabit RAM, and you can say, oh, by the way, I want one or two NVIDIA GPUs with it.

92
00:09:39.633 --> 00:09:41.932
Incoming livestream: It is a confidential computing instance.

93
00:09:42.043 --> 00:09:46.432
Incoming livestream: You can run your virtual machine images, your containers, exactly the same way.

94
00:09:46.543 --> 00:09:55.653
Incoming livestream: The management plane is the same, the control plane is the same, the operation model is exactly identical to regular virtual machines. No change.

95
00:09:56.013 --> 00:10:01.503
Incoming livestream: Okay? The added benefit? Now you are protected in use, okay?

96
00:10:01.643 --> 00:10:07.223
Incoming livestream: The rogue… an administrator at the cloud provider cannot look into what your virtual machine is.

97
00:10:08.093 --> 00:10:11.203
Incoming livestream: They can take as many snapshots as they want.

98
00:10:11.303 --> 00:10:13.142
Incoming livestream: But it's all gonna be cipher.

99
00:10:13.373 --> 00:10:16.663
Incoming livestream: the key for that one is in the CPU, so nobody else can see it.

100
00:10:17.833 --> 00:10:20.473
Incoming livestream: Or the GPUs, in case you're running it in GPUs.

101
00:10:20.733 --> 00:10:36.023
Incoming livestream: Okay? So that's the benefit of confidential computing, okay? Remember I talked to you about attestation, okay? Without attestation, confidential computing doesn't mean anything, okay? Your cloud provider told you, hey, I'm giving you an instance of confidential compute.

102
00:10:36.353 --> 00:10:38.353
Incoming livestream: But do you know for sure? You got it?

103
00:10:38.943 --> 00:10:40.803
Incoming livestream: That's where attestation comes in.

104
00:10:41.093 --> 00:10:45.492
Incoming livestream: Okay? Attestation is gonna give you a cryptographic proof that

105
00:10:45.763 --> 00:10:49.753
Incoming livestream: You are, in fact, running in a confidential computing environment.

106
00:10:50.333 --> 00:10:57.252
Incoming livestream: that is genuine to the provider of it. It could be Intel, it could be AMD, it could be NVIDIA GPUs.

107
00:10:57.413 --> 00:11:02.053
Incoming livestream: You have proof that you are running in a legitimate, confidential computing environment.

108
00:11:02.583 --> 00:11:05.113
Incoming livestream: It is patched, Correctly?

109
00:11:05.443 --> 00:11:08.172
Incoming livestream: To the level that you are satisfied with?

110
00:11:08.603 --> 00:11:14.493
Incoming livestream: And then, more importantly, your workloads that are running in are exactly what you expected them to be.

111
00:11:14.663 --> 00:11:21.572
Incoming livestream: If you're running a container, you would have a measurement of it, and you can verify that measurement to be what it needs to be.

112
00:11:22.223 --> 00:11:24.362
Incoming livestream: That's what attestation provides.

113
00:11:24.873 --> 00:11:28.182
Incoming livestream: Okay? There are multiple ways of doing attestation again.

114
00:11:28.423 --> 00:11:34.423
Incoming livestream: You can, I'm gonna come back to that previous one.

115
00:11:34.693 --> 00:11:36.962
Incoming livestream: Who provides the attestation systems?

116
00:11:38.073 --> 00:11:39.883
Incoming livestream: Is it the cloud provider?

117
00:11:40.313 --> 00:11:42.022
Incoming livestream: Or is it a third party?

118
00:11:42.373 --> 00:11:51.033
Incoming livestream: Or is do-it-yourself, okay? The question that you need to ask yourself is, Will you be comfortable?

119
00:11:51.243 --> 00:11:55.692
Incoming livestream: If the cloud provider who's giving you confidential computing environment

120
00:11:56.103 --> 00:12:00.523
Incoming livestream: is also telling you that, yeah, it's trusted, I'm giving you proof of it.

121
00:12:00.923 --> 00:12:04.533
Incoming livestream: For some workloads, it's okay. For some customers, it's perfectly fine.

122
00:12:04.683 --> 00:12:08.312
Incoming livestream: Okay? They trust the cloud provider for a lot of other things.

123
00:12:08.813 --> 00:12:11.603
Incoming livestream: So they trust on this as well, which is perfectly fine.

124
00:12:11.883 --> 00:12:18.632
Incoming livestream: But, there are a class of customers in the business segments, like regulated industries especially.

125
00:12:19.583 --> 00:12:25.963
Incoming livestream: you need that separation of duties. What, you know, in some securities domains, they call the four eyes principle.

126
00:12:26.303 --> 00:12:30.493
Incoming livestream: The provider of the infrastructure, should be different.

127
00:12:30.653 --> 00:12:35.333
Incoming livestream: Then the person who says, it's a trustworthy infrastructure that you got.

128
00:12:36.003 --> 00:12:39.063
Incoming livestream: So that's why you look at a third-party attestation system.

129
00:12:39.623 --> 00:12:47.983
Incoming livestream: Okay? Intel is one of those providers which has that independent third-party attestation system called Intel Trust Authority.

130
00:12:48.363 --> 00:12:54.303
Incoming livestream: Doesn't matter if your workloads are in Google, Azure, IBM,

131
00:12:54.793 --> 00:13:00.383
Incoming livestream: in China, whether it's Alibaba, whether it is on-prem for you.

132
00:13:00.533 --> 00:13:05.603
Incoming livestream: Intel Trust Authority has the ability to provide that verification, that attestation for you.

133
00:13:07.203 --> 00:13:11.122
Incoming livestream: Okay? So, again, I'm not saying use this versus that.

134
00:13:11.263 --> 00:13:17.592
Incoming livestream: It depends on your business, it depends on your security requirements. You have options for attestation as well.

135
00:13:18.113 --> 00:13:24.852
Incoming livestream: Okay? Now, the question somebody asked me before the session started is, Is TDX available today?

136
00:13:25.193 --> 00:13:28.742
Incoming livestream: Here is the one slider you want to take a picture of, Alex.

137
00:13:30.933 --> 00:13:37.933
Incoming livestream: So, it is available across many cloud providers. You can see the list there.

138
00:13:39.023 --> 00:13:46.962
Incoming livestream: Azure launched it a couple of days ago, you know? When I wrote this slide, it had preview next to it, which I took out today.

139
00:13:48.173 --> 00:13:51.453
Incoming livestream: You can tell it's available in many places.

140
00:13:51.643 --> 00:14:06.353
Incoming livestream: Okay? It is also available in… as part of the operating systems, so if you're doing something on-prem, you have your own AI cluster, for example, you have the ability to get it from the various OS vendors as well.

141
00:14:08.183 --> 00:14:08.853
Incoming livestream: Okay.

142
00:14:10.293 --> 00:14:10.953
Incoming livestream: No.

143
00:14:12.193 --> 00:14:15.922
Incoming livestream: a quick slide on intertrust authority before I go to the examples, right?

144
00:14:16.833 --> 00:14:20.413
Incoming livestream: I said Intel Trust Authority is that independent attestation system.

145
00:14:21.093 --> 00:14:25.583
Incoming livestream: Okay? It's available at a SaaS, it's available for on-prem deployments.

146
00:14:25.903 --> 00:14:31.392
Incoming livestream: And… Through one API, you can get attestation of your CPUs.

147
00:14:31.503 --> 00:14:40.372
Incoming livestream: and your GPUs as well. It could be one NVIDIA H100, one NVIDIA Blackwell, or it could be 8 Blackwells on the system.

148
00:14:41.103 --> 00:14:43.493
Incoming livestream: You get unified manifestation of all of that.

149
00:14:44.633 --> 00:15:01.532
Incoming livestream: Okay? And why is that important? As an application person, you don't want to deal with multiple workflows. I don't want to deal with a workflow for Intel CPUs. I don't want to deal for a workflow for NVIDIA GPUs. That's why we work together, the two companies, and we have this

150
00:15:01.783 --> 00:15:11.603
Incoming livestream: unified API, where you make one call, it figures out, hey, I am connected to two GPUs, so I need to make sure the attestation happens for both of those.

151
00:15:12.733 --> 00:15:24.952
Incoming livestream: Okay? Alright, so much for theory. Now, let me show you examples of this, okay? This is a release from Google called Google Confidential Space. How many of you heard of Confidential Space from Google?

152
00:15:26.103 --> 00:15:28.893
Incoming livestream: Maybe a few, okay. So very quickly…

153
00:15:29.193 --> 00:15:37.412
Incoming livestream: Google Confidential Space is like a data clean room for AI, okay? What it is, is you can take your containers.

154
00:15:38.163 --> 00:15:44.593
Incoming livestream: You run it in a confidential computing environment, the…

155
00:15:44.943 --> 00:15:47.783
Incoming livestream: OS that runs inside that VM,

156
00:15:48.183 --> 00:15:53.672
Incoming livestream: Your application, which is your container, Everything is measured

157
00:15:53.873 --> 00:15:57.163
Incoming livestream: And that measurements are available for verification.

158
00:15:58.503 --> 00:16:04.012
Incoming livestream: And the confidential space environment, as part of launching your container.

159
00:16:04.413 --> 00:16:07.112
Incoming livestream: will attest to Intel Trust Authority.

160
00:16:07.653 --> 00:16:16.272
Incoming livestream: And the trust authority verifies all the policies that need to be verified, and it's gonna give a token, which is called an attestation token.

161
00:16:17.063 --> 00:16:22.573
Incoming livestream: This token is now given to all the data sources.

162
00:16:23.113 --> 00:16:26.463
Incoming livestream: Whether it is a data source in Google Cloud.

163
00:16:26.573 --> 00:16:31.392
Incoming livestream: whether it's a data source in Amazon, or whether it's on-prem for you.

164
00:16:31.823 --> 00:16:34.903
Incoming livestream: That… that token is like your…

165
00:16:35.073 --> 00:16:38.562
Incoming livestream: Proof to the identity of identity.

166
00:16:38.733 --> 00:16:48.713
Incoming livestream: That your access control and management systems will verify, and based on that verification, they give access to the data to that workload.

167
00:16:49.313 --> 00:16:55.293
Incoming livestream: So, in the example that you see here, the AI workload is that green box that is there.

168
00:16:55.753 --> 00:17:03.642
Incoming livestream: The entire red box is the DDX environment. Everything inside that is measured, and it is verified.

169
00:17:03.923 --> 00:17:15.683
Incoming livestream: And that verification token is what is provided to the Google Cloud and the Amazon AWS protected resources. These are databases, keys, things like that.

170
00:17:15.883 --> 00:17:19.333
Incoming livestream: Only when those resources verify that token.

171
00:17:19.903 --> 00:17:23.533
Incoming livestream: They give the resource access token to that workload.

172
00:17:24.523 --> 00:17:34.872
Incoming livestream: And I'm sure folks who work on Google and AWS understand this very well. Without that resource access token, your workloads cannot access anything in those resources.

173
00:17:36.723 --> 00:17:41.853
Incoming livestream: Okay? The… the commitment, the security promise this gives you is

174
00:17:42.683 --> 00:17:46.893
Incoming livestream: Nobody knows what's inside that workload other than the workload owner.

175
00:17:47.703 --> 00:17:52.843
Incoming livestream: and the CPU. When it's running in the CPU, that's the only time it's in the clear.

176
00:17:53.753 --> 00:17:57.993
Incoming livestream: The data comes encrypted into that box, that red box that you see.

177
00:17:58.523 --> 00:18:03.453
Incoming livestream: the data is decrypted inside that red box. Nobody else sees it.

178
00:18:05.813 --> 00:18:24.372
Incoming livestream: Okay? This is available from Google today. They are, available on Google Cloud, and I don't know if it's available on the Google Distributed Cloud, which is their on-prem version, but it's definitely available on their Google Public Cloud. You can get a confidential space instance on a click.

179
00:18:24.393 --> 00:18:28.262
Incoming livestream: And then you can get your container workloads, and you can deploy them.

180
00:18:30.083 --> 00:18:36.133
Incoming livestream: Okay? The next example is probably something more interesting for people who are AI practitioners.

181
00:18:36.623 --> 00:18:42.533
Incoming livestream: This example is with Talus, which is a pretty well-known security company.

182
00:18:43.683 --> 00:18:48.742
Incoming livestream: there is an ISP who has an imaging model.

183
00:18:49.523 --> 00:18:54.473
Incoming livestream: And this model… Hospitals need to use this imaging model.

184
00:18:54.813 --> 00:18:57.043
Incoming livestream: So that they can fine-tune it.

185
00:18:57.243 --> 00:19:00.682
Incoming livestream: So that it's very… the efficacy of the model gets better.

186
00:19:01.343 --> 00:19:07.782
Incoming livestream: But the problem is, One hospital's data is not enough.

187
00:19:08.483 --> 00:19:10.722
Incoming livestream: To improve the efficacy of the model.

188
00:19:10.903 --> 00:19:26.592
Incoming livestream: you need the data from multiple hospitals, and we all know how important PII is, and, you know, all the HIPAA regulations and all of that. So, you have a bunch of mutually untrusting parties, or distrusting parties.

189
00:19:26.983 --> 00:19:29.483
Incoming livestream: That need to cooperate with each other.

190
00:19:29.983 --> 00:19:32.153
Incoming livestream: To improve the efficacy of the model.

191
00:19:33.603 --> 00:19:39.093
Incoming livestream: The model owner is worried that if they put the model somewhere.

192
00:19:39.363 --> 00:19:48.023
Incoming livestream: their intellectual property is… could be lost. So, they become another untrusted party as well, distrusted party in this case.

193
00:19:48.423 --> 00:19:57.042
Incoming livestream: So what do they do? They encrypt everything with the Talus CypherTrust key management system.

194
00:19:58.543 --> 00:20:08.342
Incoming livestream: So everybody, Hospital A, B, C, before they bring the data, they provision a key in the CypherTrust platform.

195
00:20:08.853 --> 00:20:14.213
Incoming livestream: They get their encryption key, and they encrypt the model, and encrypt the data sets.

196
00:20:14.983 --> 00:20:18.123
Incoming livestream: The model owner does exactly the same thing as well.

197
00:20:18.723 --> 00:20:21.642
Incoming livestream: They get the key from the CypherTrust platform.

198
00:20:21.813 --> 00:20:26.983
Incoming livestream: They encrypt their… the fine… whatever that image diagnostic model is.

199
00:20:27.353 --> 00:20:33.623
Incoming livestream: And they bring all this encrypted collateral into a confidential computing environment.

200
00:20:35.523 --> 00:20:42.033
Incoming livestream: And once the CypherTrust platform talks to an attestation system like Intel Trust Authority.

201
00:20:42.493 --> 00:20:55.332
Incoming livestream: it verifies them, and based on the individual policies, it releases the decryption keys into that trusted execution environment, the middle box that you see with CPUs and GPUs.

202
00:20:56.123 --> 00:21:04.553
Incoming livestream: The datasets get decrypted there, the model gets decrypted there, the model gets fine-tuned there for whatever period of time.

203
00:21:04.743 --> 00:21:09.173
Incoming livestream: The datasets get deleted, The model gets re-encrypted.

204
00:21:09.493 --> 00:21:11.682
Incoming livestream: Sent back to the model owner.

205
00:21:12.033 --> 00:21:18.122
Incoming livestream: Now, the model has been fully fine-tuned, With multiple hospital data.

206
00:21:19.193 --> 00:21:26.703
Incoming livestream: And it is encrypted back to the model owner, and they deliver it to the individual hospitals.

207
00:21:27.493 --> 00:21:34.123
Incoming livestream: So what did we get with this thing? The model owner's IP is protected. There is guarantee that nobody

208
00:21:34.273 --> 00:21:37.183
Incoming livestream: Saw what's in the model, nobody can steal the model.

209
00:21:37.763 --> 00:21:40.952
Incoming livestream: The data sets that are coming from the various hospitals.

210
00:21:42.033 --> 00:21:45.613
Incoming livestream: Nobody sees the data except the model training process.

211
00:21:46.523 --> 00:21:49.883
Incoming livestream: So, their security requirements are met as well.

212
00:21:50.123 --> 00:21:57.043
Incoming livestream: And then the ultimate benefit is the efficacy of the model got better, because it got trained on multiple hospital data sets.

213
00:21:58.323 --> 00:22:10.562
Incoming livestream: Okay? The last example I'm going to show you is agentic AI and confidential computing, okay? I'm sure everybody has their own picture of what an agent is and what it does. This is my picture.

214
00:22:10.923 --> 00:22:16.363
Incoming livestream: Okay? Has a bunch of, MCP servers, not surprisingly.

215
00:22:16.543 --> 00:22:18.362
Incoming livestream: Talking to different tools.

216
00:22:18.633 --> 00:22:27.173
Incoming livestream: There's a reasoning engine with a language model, a big language model, so that I know what my plans are, all the reasoning stuff happens there.

217
00:22:27.543 --> 00:22:33.243
Incoming livestream: But I also have domain models, okay? This is where Agentic AI is going, in my view.

218
00:22:33.423 --> 00:22:36.193
Incoming livestream: It's not one large model doing everything.

219
00:22:36.293 --> 00:22:42.452
Incoming livestream: Enterprises are gonna have a lot of localized domain models, which are very efficient.

220
00:22:42.473 --> 00:22:58.692
Incoming livestream: very effective, and then the security guarantees are there. So, you're gonna have a bunch of local domain models, you have rags feeding them, all of that stuff. But, the important thing is MCP servers will run in confidential computing. That's what the red box is.

221
00:22:58.833 --> 00:23:05.243
Incoming livestream: There are various flavors for that one. You can just run the MCP server itself in confidential computing.

222
00:23:05.343 --> 00:23:09.622
Incoming livestream: You can run the MCP server with the tool in confidential computing.

223
00:23:10.463 --> 00:23:17.612
Incoming livestream: These small lang… these small domain models, the SLMs and RAGs, can absolutely run in confidential computing as well.

224
00:23:18.783 --> 00:23:22.742
Incoming livestream: Okay? So this is where the industry is going for agentic AI.

225
00:23:22.893 --> 00:23:29.242
Incoming livestream: Okay? There is an organization called COSI, Coalition for Secure AI,

226
00:23:29.373 --> 00:23:38.273
Incoming livestream: Most of the big, security companies, cloud providers, hardware providers, all of them are part of COSI.

227
00:23:38.443 --> 00:23:44.183
Incoming livestream: And COSI recently published a MCP security positioning paper.

228
